## Philosophy

The economy is designed around **player trade**. The admin shop exists as a fallback, not as the main market. High-end items come from players, exploration, crafting, quests, contracts, or auctions.

If you want an elytra, you buy it from a player. If you want high-tier tools, you buy them from a player. If you want shulker boxes, rare materials, or advanced machinery — you find a player who has them.

<InfoCallout type="info" title="Economy Balance Notice">
  New Prosperity is in Season 0/Beta. Economy values, prices, rewards, and sink rates may be adjusted during testing based on observed inflation, deflation, and player feedback.
</InfoCallout>

## Money Faucets

Money enters the economy through controlled channels:

- **Jobs** — Regular payment for work done in your profession
- **Public contracts** — Completing development contracts for the city
- **Quests** — One-time or repeatable story and task quests
- **Admin shop sales** — Selling basic resources to the admin shop at controlled rates
- **Auctions** — Bidding on rare server-distributed items

Money faucets are designed to be limited and tied to productive activity.

## Money Sinks

Money leaves the economy through:

- **Plot and land purchases** — Buying land from the city
- **Licenses** — Required for advanced activities (driving vehicles, running certain companies, industrial operations)
- **Upkeep costs** — Machinery, vehicles, and high-end assets cost money to maintain
- **Fines** — In-game law violations result in fines paid to the city or victims
- **Public contract funding** — Players can also fund contracts (paying in, not out)
- **Taxes** — Plot taxes are paid periodically

Sinks exist to prevent inflation and ensure that money in the economy represents real value.

## Admin Shop Limits

The admin shop is deliberately limited:

- **Does not sell**: Elytras, shulker boxes, totems of undying, high-tier tools, vehicles, rare enchantment books, or advanced machinery
- **Does sell**: Basic materials at capped quantities per day to prevent abuse
- **Buying**: The admin shop buys basic resources at controlled rates with daily limits

The admin shop is not the market. It is a pressure valve.

## Player Shops

Player shops are the real economy:

- Any player with a **Merchant license** (or above) can open a shop
- Shops are located in purchased or rented commercial plots in the market district
- Shops set their own prices — supply and demand drive the market
- Player shops should consistently beat admin shop prices on common goods

If you want to be rich, open a shop and supply what people need.

## Land as Wealth Progression

Land is one of the most important assets:

- **Starter plots** — Small residential plots near spawn, affordable for new players
- **Commercial plots** — Market district shops, priced higher, used for selling
- **Industrial land** — Required for factories, farms, and production systems
- **Development projects** — Unlocked through community funding, new land is added over time

Owning land is a milestone. It is not just a home — it is a store of value.

## Licenses

Licenses are required for advanced activities:

| License | Required For |
|---|---|
| Merchant | Opening a player shop |
| Industrialist | Operating machinery and semi-auto production |
| Vehicle Operator | Driving wheeled or aerial vehicles |
| Builder | Taking on large public construction contracts |
| Company Formation | Starting a company with employees |

Licenses cost money and may require skill tree progress to unlock.

## Public Contracts

Public contracts are the bridge between player productivity and world development:

- The city posts contracts for needed resources: timber, stone, food, materials
- Players complete contracts and are paid by the city treasury
- The resources are removed from the player's inventory and used to build public infrastructure
- This is the primary intended money faucet for active players

Public contracts keep the economy moving and give new players a direct way to earn.

## Inflation Control

The server uses several mechanisms to control inflation:

- **Daily limits** on admin shop buying prices
- **Periodic balance reviews** — Staff review median player wealth monthly
- **Sink rate adjustments** — License prices and taxes may be raised if inflation is detected
- **Limited money faucets** — Contracts, jobs, and quests are gated by time or quantity

If inflation becomes a problem during beta, values will be adjusted.

